{"key":"processedPost-12818599","value":{"id":12818599,"first":12817802,"last":12818947,"when":1277759005,"utime":"06/29/10 12:03 AM","content":"If you have a 250 ml jar, you can use it to measure 'cups' by volume. It won't be exact, but close enough for what we're doing.&nbsp; For things like casing layer prep, manure prep, etc., you're going to squeeze the excess water out anyway(or add more) when you test for field capacity.&nbsp; For the BRF Tek, the ratio is 2-1-1, whether you use cups, quarts, liters, or truckloads. <br /><br />Volume to weight measurements really only work with water, and I agree that the metric system makes things much easier.&nbsp; I always have to chuckle at my fellow Americans who think the metric system is 'hard to figure out' but they have no problem counting money. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/><br />RR","title":"Re: Measurements conversion from volume to weight?"}}